If I was gonna die anyways I should’ve drank more…
I wish I drank some more…

“Hurry up and get down here!” the bartender bellows, whilst propping open the bunker door.

The screams from upstairs pierce my eardrums, and the thunder of shoes hitting the pavement shakes the ground.

[Hallo Bar] is known for being built over the previous owner’s old bunker. Mainly used for storage, it doesn’t hold its previous glory of safety, but right now, it’s the best we have.

I rush inside, and the people behind start piling in shortly after. I move further into the storage space, expecting to hear the heavy click of the bunker’s hatch, but it never comes.

I turn my head around. There’s no one else left, but the old man just stands at the entryway, head turned… towards us.

“What the **** are you doing,” I say. “Close the door!”

I push past everyone and make for the handle. But, seeing this, he only steps back and widens the door.

“No…” he whispers, like a plea to himself.

I get to him and start wrestling his hands off the door. I can hear booming footsteps make their way down the stairs outside, heavy and unnatural. Any longer, and we’re done for.

“What the **** are you doing,” I repeat.

In the struggle, a swinging light casts its ray over his face, allowing me to get a good look at it for the first time. His skin is pale, hairline beaded with sweat. His pupils are dilated, but most importantly, they aren’t looking at me. He continues to stare into the group inside the bunker, muttering to himself.

“You’ve turned. No… we’ll all be dead.”

“What are you talking about?” I plead. “It’s getting closer, close the damn door!” My distress seems to trigger him, and he snaps out of his shock with a roar.

“Get out! Get the **** out!”

He throws me off of him. The people inside cower, confused with the old bartender’s sudden outburst. None of them move. The booming draws near.

It’s coming closer.

“You’re not human! You’ll turn all of us!”

Outside, just beyond the door, I see the shadow of something, unmoving, as if waiting for the opportunity to strike and kill.

We’re going to die.

“I said get-”

Before he finishes his sentence, I shove him out into the hallway. Behind him, a dark blur lashes out, and he lets out a blood-curdling scream.

I spend no time thinking about the weight of what I’ve just done. With shaking hands, I grip the door and haul it shut.

